  "text": "Almost all the ambient backscatter transmitter designs are specific to a certain signal source, e.g., Wi-Fi or TV signals. However, in many cases, the signal from the specific source is not available. Therefore, UWB backscatter techniques are introduced [CITATION_1] . The techniques allow the backscatter transmitter to use a wide variety of ambient sources operating in the 80 MHz to 900 MHz range such as FM radios, digital TVs, and cellular networks. However, different signals from different sources have different characteristics and patterns. Thus, it is important to optimize the backscatter transmission strategies, e.g., using FM bands and digital TV jointly to optimize network throughput.",
  "correct_citation": {
